('BasilicaSaintAlphonsusPagani', 'Basilica di Sant’Alfonso<br>Piazza Sant’Alfonso 1, <br>84016 Pagani, Italy <br><br>*A wooden statue of Saint Alphonsus Liguori (d. 1787) rests under an altar to the left of the main sanctuary. This statue is so life like that at first glance one may think that the entire body of Saint Alphonsus Liguori is incorrupt. However, this is not the case. Some relics of the saint, nevertheless, are present. They rest on a silver carriage below the wooden statue.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintAmbroseVenice', 'Basilica di Sant’Ambrogio<br>Piazza Sant’Ambrogio 15, <br>20123 Milano, Italy <br><br>*Saint Ambrose (d. 397) was the bishop of this city for over 20 years. It was during this time that Saint Augustine (d. 430) heard Saint Ambrose’s powerful preaching and became attracted to the Christian faith. Today the body of Saint Ambrose, dressed in white pontifical vestments, rests within an urn in the crypt of this church. Lying beside his remains are the bodies of two additional saints, the martyrs Gervasius and Protasius.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintAnthonyAbbotSaintFrancesXavierCabrini', 'Basilica di Sant’Antonio Abate e Santa Francesca Cabrini<br>Via Umberto I, <br>Sant’Angelo Lodigiano, Italy <br><br>*Construction of this beautiful church began in 1928 and was completed ten years later. A bone from Saint Frances Xavier Cabrini (d. 1917) rests within a marble altar in the chapel dedicated in her name. <br>*Saint Frances Xavier Cabrini was also born in this city. Her childhood home is reconstructed into a museum and can be visited.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintAnthonyPadua', 'Basilica di Sant’Antonio da Padova<br>Piazza del Santo 11, <br>35123 Padova, Italy <br><br>The tomb of Saint Anthony of Padua (d. 1231) is within a chapel on the left side of the nave. His tomb was opened in 1981 and contains the bones of the saint.<br>Within the apse of the church is the Treasury Chapel. This chapel contains three niches. The central niche preserves three important relics of Saint Anthony of Padua. These include his lower jaw, his incorrupt tongue, and cartilage from his larynx. All three of these relics are used in speech and reflect the saint’s great ability as a preacher.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintApollinarisRavenna', 'Basilica di Sant’Apollinare in Classe<br>Via Romea Sud 224 <br>48124, Classe Ravenna, Italy<br><br>The bones of Saint Apollinaris rest within the main altar of this church. <br>A debate arose in Ravenna during the 12th century whether the relics of Saint Apollinaris were within the Basilica di Sant’Apollinare Nuovo or within the Basilica di Sant’Apollinare in Classe. After examining the evidence Pope Alexander III determined that the relics rested within the Basilica di Sant’Apollinare in Classe. An empty tomb within this church dated 1173 AD preserves the memory of this declaration. This tomb is below the small marble altar in the center of the nave of the church. The bones of Saint Apollinaris were transferred to the main altar in the 18th century.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintAugustineRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di Sant\'Agostino<br>Piazza Sant\'Agostino<br><br>Relics of Saint Monica (d. 387), the mother of Augustine, rest in the chapel to the left of the main altar.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintBartholomewBenevento', 'Basilica di San Bartolomeo<br>Piazza Federico Torre <br>Benevento, Italy <br><br>*A tradition holds that the relics of Saint Bartholomew were transferred to Benevento, Italy in the 9th century. A century later they were transferred to Rome. Benevento, however, continues to claim possession of the true relics of Saint Bartholomew. These relics are placed within a porphyry urn below the main altar. An additional bone fragment is placed within a bust of the saint. Twice a year, on August 24th and October 25th, the city celebrates in honor of the saint.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintBernardineSienaLAquila', 'Basilica di San Bernardino<br>Via San Bernardino <br>67100 L’Aquila, Italy <br><br>*On April 6, 2009 an earthquake hit the Italian city of L’Aquila and severely damaged the Basilica of San Bernardino. As a result the relics of Saint Bernardine of Siena (d.1444) were removed from this church. At present they rest within a church dedicated to Saint Bernardine of Siena at Piazza d’Armi along Via Ugo Piccinini in L’Aquila. However, once the necessary repairs to the basilica are completed the relics will be returned to their original resting place within the basilica.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintBlaiseMaratea', 'Basilica di San Biagio<br>Via Castello <br>Maratea, Italy <br><br>Relics of Saint Blaise (d. 316) were brought to this city in 732 AD and now rest within this church.  They are located within a white marble urn located below a silver bust of the saint.  Also of note is the large 68 foot tall statue of Christ the Redeemer that overlooks the sea just a short distance from this church.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintCeciliaRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di Santa Cecilia in Trastevere<br>22 Piazza di Santa Cecilia<br><br>In 821 the body of Saint Cecilia was exhumed from the Catacombs of Saint Callixtus by Pope Saint Paschal I (d. 824) and brought to this church. Today her body rests within the crypt under the main altar.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintClareAssisi', 'Basilica di Santa Chiara<br>Piazza Santa Chiara <br>06081 Assisi, Italy <br><br>*The remains of Saint Clare (d. 1253) are enshrined within the crypt of this church. <br>*Also within the large chapel on the right side of this church is the San Damiano Crucifix that spoke to Saint Francis of Assisi. (This is the chapel where Morning Prayer and Evening Prayer are prayed)', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintClementRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di San Clemente<br>Via di San Giovanni in Laterano<br><br>The remains of Pope Saint Clement I (d. 80) and of Saint Ignatius of Antioch (d. 107) rest beneath the main altar.<br><br>A chapel on the right side of the nave is dedicated to Saints Cyril (d. 869) and Methodius (d. 885). The relic of Saint Cyril found in the 1960’s rests within the altar of this chapel.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintDominicBologna', 'Basilica di San Domenico<br>Piazza San Domenico <br>40124 Bologna, Italy <br><br>The remains of Saint Dominic (d. 1221) rest within this church in an exquisite tomb called the Arca di San Domenico. This tomb is placed in a large side chapel on the right side of the nave. The relic of Saint Dominic’s skull is enshrined within a reliquary on the backside of this tomb.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintDominicSiena', 'Basilica di San Domenico<br>Piazza San Domenico <br>53100 Siena, Italy <br><br>*The head of Saint Catherine of Siena (d. 1380) rests within a chapel on the right side of the nave. <br>*Also a finger of the saint is venerated within a reliquary case just to the right of this chapel. This relic has traditionally been used to impart a blessing on the Italian military.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintFrancisAssisi', 'Basilica di San Francesco D’Assisi<br>Piazza San Francesco 2, <br>06081 Assisi, Italy <br><br>*Saint Francis of Assisi (d. 1226) is buried in the crypt of this church.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintFrancisPaola', 'Basilica di San Francesco di Paola<br>Largo San Francesco di Paola <br>87027 Paola, Italy <br><br>In 1482 King Louis XI of France requested that Saint Francis of Paola be at his side as he neared death. Saint Francis at first was reluctant to accept the king’s request because he did not want to leave his native Italy. However, upon the urging of Pope Sixtus IV he acquiesced. Saint Francis of Paola would then remain in France for the next 25 years providing counsel to the French kings. He died in 1507 and was buried in Plessis. In 1562 his tomb was violently reopened, his incorrupt body plundered, and the majority of his relics destroyed by French Huguenots. Some of his bones, however, escaped destruction and were later taken to Paola, Italy. These bones now rest within this church.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintGeorgeInVelabro', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di San Giorgio in Velabro<br>19 Via del Velabro<br><br>Part of the skull of Saint George megalomartyr rests beneath the main altar.<br><br>Many legends surround this early Christian martyr. The most famous involves him slaying a dragon. Critical research in the last century has upheld the existence of Saint George; however, it has cast doubts upon many of his legendary accounts. (Note: Other shrines throughout the world also claim to have the relic of his skull.)</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintJohnLateran', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di San Giovanni in Laterano<br>Piazza San Giovanni in Laterano 4<br><br>Positioned above the Papal Altar are two busts of Saint Peter and Saint Paul. According to tradition the skulls or parts of the skulls of Saints Peter and Paul are within these busts. Also located within the Papal Altar is a wooden table that Saint Peter and many of the earliest popes are said to have celebrated the Eucharist upon.<br><br>Located to the left of the Papal Altar is another very ancient table. This table rests above the altar where the Blessed Sacrament is reserved. It is placed directly behind a bronze relief of the Last Supper. Tradition claims that it was upon this table that Jesus and the apostles celebrated the Last Supper. Another section of the \"table of the Last Supper\" is kept in the Holy of Holies, within the Church of the Holy Stairs across the street.<br><br>Also the tomb of Pope Leo XIII (d. 1903) is to the left of the Papal Altar.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintLawrenceOutsideTheWalls', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di San Lorenzo fuori le Mura<br>3 Piazzale del Verano<br><br>The remains of Saint Lawrence, Saint Stephen, and Saint Justin lie in the <i>confessio</i>below the main altar. (Note: The relics are labeled as Saint Justin the Presbyter. Therefore, it is likely that this is not Saint Justin the Martyr.)<br><br>A marble stone slab beneath the choir floor is said to be the stone on which Saint Lawrence was placed after his execution. Also enshrined in this lower area is the body of Blessed Pius IX Pope(d. 1878).</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintLucyTombSyracuse', 'Basilica di Santa Lucia al Sepolcro <br>Via Luigi Bignami 1, <br>96100 Syracuse, Sicily, Italy <br><br>This church marks the spot where Saint Lucy (d. 304) was martyred. <br>Within the octagonal baptistery adjacent to this church is the grave where Saint Lucy was originally buried. Under the altar is a beautiful marble statue depicting the saint.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintMarkEvangelistRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di San Marco evangelista al Campidoglio<br>Palazzo Venezia, Piazza di S. Marco, 48, 00186 Roma RM<br><br>Little is known of Mark\'s early life. According to the Liber Pontificalis, he was a Roman, and his father\'s name was Priscus. Mark succeeded Sylvester I as pope on 18 January 336.<br><br>Some evidence suggests that the early lists of bishops and martyrs known as the Depositio episcoporum and Depositio martyrum were begun during his pontificate. According to the Liber Pontificalis, Pope Mark issued a constitution investing the bishop of Ostia with a pallium and confirming his power to consecrate newly elected popes. Likewise according to the Liber Pontificalis, Pope Mark is credited with the foundation of the Basilica of San Marco, a basilica in Rome, and a cemetery church over the Catacomb of Balbina, just outside the city on lands obtained as a donation from Emperor Constantine.<br><br>Mark died of natural causes on 7 October and was buried in the catacomb of Balbina. In 1048, his remains were removed to the town of Velletri, and from 1145 were relocated to the Basilica of San Marco in Rome, where they are kept in an urn under the altar. His feast day is celebrated on 7 October. He is particularly venerated at the Abbadia San Salvatore at Monte Amiata.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintMarkVenice', '<p class=\"justify\"><img alt=\"Saint Marks Basilica\" src=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Venezia_Basilica_di_San_Marco_Fassade_2.jpg/320px-Venezia_Basilica_di_San_Marco_Fassade_2.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"214\" class=\"entityImage\" />The first Basilica was founded in the 9th century to house the mortal remains of St Mark the Evangelist, brought back to Italy from Egypt by Venetian merchants. According to christian tradition, Mark the Evangelist founded the church of Alexandria, one of the most important episcopal sees of early Christianity. His feast day is celebrated on April 25, and his symbol is the winged lion.</p><p class=\"justify\">Saint Mark became the travel companion and interpreter for Saint Peter during his travels throughout Asia Minor (1 Peter 1:1), after Peter was miraculously freed by angels from his imprisonment by Herod Agrippa I (Eusebius of Caesarea, Eccl. Hist. 2.9.1–4; Acts 12:1–19). Mark the Evangelist wrote down the sermons of Peter, thus composing the Gospel according to Mark (Eccl. Hist. 15–16), before he left for Alexandria in the third year of Claudius (AD 43). According to Acts 15:39, Mark went to Cyprus with Barnabas after the Council of Jerusalem; then in AD 49 (about 19 years after the Ascension of Jesus) Mark travelled to Alexandria and founded the Church of Alexandria. Today, the Coptic Orthodox Church, the Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria, and the Coptic Catholic Church trace their origins to this community. Aspects of the Coptic liturgy can be traced back to Mark himself. He became the first bishop of Alexandria and he is honored as the founder of Christianity in Africa.</p><p class=\"linkBookVisitContainer\"><a class=\"linkBookVisit\" href=\"https://www.omniaforitaly.org\">Book your visit</a></p>', '<p class=\"justify\"><img alt=\"Saint Marks Basilica\" src=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Venezia_Basilica_di_San_Marco_Fassade_2.jpg/320px-Venezia_Basilica_di_San_Marco_Fassade_2.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"214\" class=\"entityImage\" />La prima Basilica fu fondata nel sec. IX per ospitare i resti mortali di San Marco l\\\'Evangelista, portati in Italia dall\\\'Egitto da alcuni mercanti veneziani. Secondo la tradizione cristiana, San Marco l\\\'Evangelista fondò la chiesa di Alessandria, una delle più importanti sedi del cristianesimo antico. La sua festa viene celebrata il 25 Aprile, e suo simbolo è il leone alato.</p><p class=\"justify\">San Marco fu compagno di viaggio e interprete per San Pietro durante il viaggio da lui compiuto nell\\\'Asia Minore (1 Pietro 1,1), a seguito della miracolosa liberazione per intervento degli angeli dall\\\'imprigionamento da parte di Erode Agrippa I (Eusebio di Caesarea, Eccl. Hist. 2.9.1–4; Atti 12,1–19). San Marco l\\\'Evangelista appuntò i sermoni di Pietro, e così compose il Vangelo a lui attribuito (Eccl. Hist. 15–16), prima di partire per Alessandria nell\\\'anno terzo di Claudio (43 d.C.). Secondo Atti 15,39, Marco andò a Cipro con Barnaba dopo il Concilio di Gerusalemme; poi nel 49 d.C. (circa 19 anni dopo l\\\'Ascensione di Gesù) in Egitto dove fondò la chiesa di Alessandria; ad oggi la Chiesa Copta Ortodossa, la Chiesa Greco-ortodossa di Alessandria, e la Chiesa Copta Cattolica si fanno risalire a questa stessa comunità. Certi aspetti della liturgia Copta risalgono fino a San Marco. Fu il primo vescovo di Alessandria e viene onorato come il fondatore del cristianesimo nel continente africano.</p><p class=\"linkBookVisitContainer\"><a class=\"linkBookVisit\" href=\"https://www.omniaforitaly.org\">Prenota la visita</a></p>', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintMaryKevelaer', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintMaryMajor', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di Santa Maria Maggiore<br>42 Piazza di Santa Maria Maggiore<br><br>Some relics of Saint Matthias rest within the porphyry urn that makes up the base of the Papal Altar. Also in the <i>confessio</i>below this altar are five pieces of wood believed to be from the crib of Jesus Christ.<br><br>Enshrined within the large chapel in the right transept is the body of Pope Saint Pius V (d. 1572). His remains rest within an urn on the left side of this chapel.<br><br>The remains of Saint Jerome (d. 420) were brought to this basilica in the 12th century. There is some doubt as to their exact location. They either rest under the Papal Altar within the main body of the church or within the <i>confessio</i>in the right transept.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintNicholasBari', 'Basilica di San Nicola<br>Largo Abate Elia <br>70122 Bari, Italy <br><br>Relics of Saint Nicholas (d. 350) rest within a small urn located under the altar in the crypt of this church.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintPancras', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di San Pancrazio<br>Piazza San Pancrazio 5/D<br><br>The church was built on the site of the tomb of Saint Pancras.<br><br>In 1798 a general under Napoleon Bonaparte invaded Rome and established the Roman Republic. During this time intruders entered the church of San Pancrazio and severely damaged the remains of Saint Pancras. His head, however, was left untouched since it was kept at the Basilica of Saint John Lateran from 850 to 1966. In 1966 Pope Paul VI restored the head of Saint Pancras to the church of San Pancrazio. It now rests within a reliquary bust on the right side of the nave<br><br>.The porphyry urn that makes up the base of the main altar is said to contain relics from early martyrs including a few relics from Saint Pancras.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintSebastianRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di San Sebastiano fuori le Mura<br>136 Via Appia Antica<br><br>The last chapel on the right side of the nave is dedicated to Pope Saint Fabian (d. 250). Also a reliquary chapel near the center of the church on the right side of the nave contains relics of the saint. Saint Fabian was originally buried in the Catacombs of San Callixtus but later his remains were moved to this church. Also within this same chapel are the column to which Saint Sebastian was tied, an arrow that pierced his flesh, and some small relics from a number of other saints including Saint Peter, Saint Paul, and Saint Andrew.<br></br>Directly across from this chapel and on the left side of the nave is a chapel dedicated to Saint Sebastian (d. 288). Saint Sebastian was originally buried in the catacombs located under this church. At some point, however, these remains were removed. Some of these remains are now located within an urn in this chapel below the very impressive statue of Saint Sebastian created by Giuseppe Giorgetti.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintThomasOrtona', 'Basilica di San Tommaso Apostolo<br>Corso Giacomo Matteotti 35, <br>66026 Ortona, Italy <br><br>The relics of Saint Thomas the Apostle rest within a golden casket placed within a white marble altar located in the crypt of this church.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSaintVincentCatherineRicciPrato', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>A female Dominican monastery dedicated to Saint Vincent Ferrer was founded at the start of the 16th century, which then gained a significant importance a half century later thanks to the influence of Sister Catherine de\' Ricci.<br><br>The church, completed at the end of the 16th century, was completely renovated after Catherine de\' Ricci\'s canonization. Her spirituality greatly influenced florentine and tuscan society in the 18th century, so much so that she became the prime example of mysticism even above Saint Mary Magdalen de\' Pazzi.<br><br>The church was promoted to the rank of minor basilica when her body was placed under the main altar.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaSanSaturninoCagliari', 'Basilica di San Saturnino<br>d. 304 AD', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaStAgnesInAgoneRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di Saint\'Agnese in Agone<br>Piazza Navona<br><br>According to tradition Saint Agnes was martyred at this location in 304 AD. A relic of her skull is present in a chapel located to the left of the main sanctuary.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BasilicaStAgnesOutsideTheWallsRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Basilica di Saint\'Agnese fuori le Mura<br>Via S Agnese 315<br><br>The bones of Saint Agnes (d. 304) rest in the crypt under the main sanctuary.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('BirthplaceSaintGregoryMaryGrassi', 'Via S. Gregorio Maria Grassi, 65<br>Martyred in Taiyuan during the boxer revolution in China.<br>There is a plaque here commemorating him.', 'Via S. Gregorio Maria Grassi, 65<br>Martirizzato a Taiyuan durante la rivoluzione boxer in Cina.<br>C\'è una targa qui per ricordarlo.', '', '', '', ''),
('CatacombsSaintCallixtus', '<p class=\"justify\">The body of Saint Cyprian (d. 253 at Civitavecchia) was buried here in the year 283.<br><br> Saint Cecilia was buried here<br><br>Sixteen popes have been buried in the catacombs of Saint Callixtus, though the burial place of Pope Saint Zephyrinus is uncertain.<ul><li>Pope Saint Zephyrinus (?)</li><li>Pope Saint Urban I</li><li>Pope Saint Pontian</li><li>Pope Saint Anterus</li><li>Pope Saint Fabian</li><li>Pope Saint Cornelius</li><li>Pope Saint Lucius I</li><li>Pope Saint Stephen I</li><li>Pope Saint Sixtus II</li><li>Pope Saint Dionysius</li><li>Pope Saint Felix I</li><li>Pope Saint Eutichianus</li><li>Pope Saint Caius</li><li>Pope Saint Eusebius</li><li>Pope Saint Miltiades</li><li>Pope Saint Damasus I</li></ul>There are no longer any human remains in the catacombs (at least in the areas that have been excavated so far) seeing that the Superintendence of Cultural Heritage of the city of Rome decided to move all human remains to the Basilica of Saint Praxedes (to prevent tourists from pillaging fragments or relics, as was quite common in the middle ages).</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralAquino', 'Cattedrale di Aquino<br>Piazza San Tommaso d’Aquino <br>03031 Aquino, Italy <br><br>In 1963 the Archbishop of Toulouse, Gabriel Marie Garrone, gave to this church a small rib bone of Saint Thomas Aquinas (d. 1274). <br>*The relic is carried in procession every year on the evening of March 7th.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralAssumptionSiena', 'Cattedrale di Santa Maria Assunta<br>Piazza del Duomo 8, <br>53100 Siena, Italy <br><br>In May of 1464 Pope Pius II presented to this church the right arm of Saint John the Baptist. This relic now rests on the left side of the nave behind the Chapel of Saint John the Baptist.Each year this relic is presented for public veneration prior to the saint’s feast day on June 24th.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralBrescia', 'Duomo Nuovo<br>Piazza Paolo VI <br>25121 Brescia, Italy <br><br>An arm bone of Saint Benedict rests within this church. It is placed in front of the beautiful funerary monument dedicated to Saint Apollonio on the right side of the nave. Around the year 759 this relic was given to a Benedictine community in Leno, located just south of Brescia. During the 15th century it was transferred to Brescia.<br>Recently this bone has been rigorously studied in an attempt to authenticate the relics in either Monte Cassino or Saint-Benoît-sur-Loire. Documentation shows that this bone came from Montecassino in 759. This late date provides evidence that at least some relics of the saint were still preserved in Montecassino following the alleged theft in the 7th century. On the other hand, recent studies seem to indicate that the physical characteristics of this bone from Brescia do not match the Montecassino source.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralCatania', 'Duomo di Catania<br>Piazza del Duomo <br>95131 Catania, Sicily, Italy <br><br>*The relics of Saint Agatha (d. 251) are located within the apse of this church in the Chapel of Saint Agatha. Unfortunately, this chapel is not accessible to the public. However, every year on February 4th and 5th the relics are brought out and the faithful are given the chance to participate in the procession of her relics throughout the streets of Catania.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralFaenza', 'Duomo di Faenza<br>Piazza XI Febbraio <br>48018 Faenza, Italy <br><br>*Saint Peter Damian (d. 1072) who was born in the nearby town of Ravenna always retained a strong connection to Faenza. It was here that he studied early in life and later where he founded a hermitage and a monastery. He was known in life as a reformer, a scholar, and a diplomat. He died in Faenza and his remains were interred in a monastery within this city until in 1826 they were transferred to the cathedral. They can now be found solemnly displayed within an urn in the sixth chapel on the left side of the nave.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralFlorence', 'Duomo di Firenze<br><br>Relics of the following four saints are said to be within the sacristy of this church. <br>*The skull of Saint John Chrysostom (Acquired in 1360), an arm of Saint Andrew the Apostle (Acquired in the 14th century), an arm of Saint Philip the Apostle (Acquired in 1205), and a finger of Saint John the Baptist (Acquired in 1419). <br>*It is said that this is the same finger that Saint John the Baptist used to point at Jesus when he proclaimed, “Behold the Lamb of God.”', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralMilan', 'Duomo di Milano<br>Piazza del Duomo 18, <br>20122 Milano, Italy <br><br>The remains of Saint Charles Borromeo (d. 1584) rest within the crypt of this church. Access to this crypt is located on the right side of the main sanctuary. Saint Charles was a greatly beloved bishop of this city during the late 16th century. <br>*Located below this church is an ancient baptistery. It was here that Saint Ambrose baptized Saint Augustine in 387 AD.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralMonreale', 'Cattedrale di Monreale<br>Piazza Guglielmo II 1, <br>90046 Monreale, Palermo, Sicily, Italy <br><br>The innards of King Saint Louis IX of France (d. 1270) rest within an urn in the left transept of this church. These relics were acquired during the transfer of Saint Louis’ body from Tunis to Paris.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', '');
INSERT IGNORE INTO `i18n__description` (`id_key`, `EN`, `IT`, `ES`, `FR`, `DE`, `PT`) VALUES
('CathedralNaples', 'Duomo di Napoli<br>Via Duomo 147, <br>80138 Naples, Italy <br><br>Saint Januarius (d. 305) is most well known for the liquefaction of his blood. This miracle occurs annually on September 19th, December 16th, and the first Saturday in May. <br>*The relics of Saint Januarius can be found in three different locations within this church. His blood, which is sealed in a reliquary, is placed upon the altar in the second chapel on the right side of the nave. This exquisite chapel also contains fifty-one silver busts, each depicting a different saint. They were donated to this church by various guilds and ecclesial institutions in the city. The second location, found in the confessio below the main sanctuary, preserves the bones of the saint. These bones, which are visible, rest within a vase below the altar in this confessio. Finally, fragments of his skull rest within a bust placed in the museum located next to this church. This bust is placed next to a lighted candle within an upper room in this museum.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralNola', 'Cattedrale di Nola<br>Piazza Duomo 1, <br>80035 Nola, Italy <br><br>On June 22nd crowds of people fill the square in front of this church for the annual celebration of Saint Paulinus (d. 431). A silver bust of the saint is processed into the crowd and eight festive obelisks and an ornamental wooden boat are blessed. The obelisks and boat harken back to a legendary story of the saint. It is said that as Barbarian tribes were invading Italy, Saint Paulinus offered to be taken captive in exchange for the return of a widow’s son. Shortly thereafter a Turkish sultan, being so impressed by Saint Paulinus’ selfless act of love, decided to grant him his freedom. Saint Paulinus then returned to Italy and was warmly welcomed by the people of Nola. *Apart from this celebration relics also rest within this church in the fourth chapel on the left side of the nave.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralPriverno', 'Cattedrale di Santa Maria Annunziata<br>Piazza Vittorio Emanuele <br>Priverno, Italy <br><br>A relic of the purported skull of Saint Thomas Aquinas rests within this church. The authenticity of the relic is dubious. A spurious discovery of the relic in 1585 is presumed by some to be a forgery. Nevertheless annually on the evening of March 6th the Bishop of the Diocese leads a procession through the streets of Priverno carrying the relic of the skull. (March 7th was the Feast Day of Saint Thomas Aquinas on the old calendar.)', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralSaintAndrewAmalfi', 'Duomo di Sant\'Andrea<br>Piazza Duomo <br>84011 Amalfi, Italy <br><br>Tradition claims that Saint Andrew was martyred and buried in Patras, Greece. Later most of his relics were transferred to Constantinople. In the year 1204, after the Crusaders sacked Constantinople, the relics were taken west to the city of Amalfi, Italy. Some of these relics remain here today. They rest beneath the main altar in the crypt of this church.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralSaintBartholomewLipari', 'Cattedrale di San Bartolomeo<br>Via del Concordato <br>Lipari, Sicily, Italy <br><br>A relic of the thumb of Saint Bartholomew rests within a silver arm reliquary in this church. This relic is exposed for veneration during feast days of the saint.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralSaintBonaventureBagnoregio', 'Cattedrale San Bonaventura<br>Piazza Cavour<br>01022 Bagnoregio, Italy<br><br>The only remaining relic of Saint Bonaventure (d. 1274), his right arm, rests within a chapel on the right side of the nave of this church. This relic was brought to Bagnoregio in 1491 as a gift since the saint’s birth home is in the nearby hill city of Civita di Bagnoregio. This transfer was providential because a little less than a century later, in 1562, his tomb in Lyon, France was plundered by French Huguenots and his remains were burned in the public square. During this event his incorrupt head was preserved; however, several centuries later during the French Revolution it disappeared and has remained missing ever since.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralSaintCassianImola', 'Cattedrale di San Cassiano<br>Piazza Duomo 1, <br>40026 Imola, Bologna, Italy <br><br>*Saint Peter Chrysologus was born in this city in 406 AD. He eventually became the Bishop of Ravenna and was known for his outstanding homilies. One hundred seventy-six of these homilies survive to this day. <br>*The remains of Saint Peter Chrysologus rest within an altar in the crypt of this church. Kindly ask the sacristan for access. The relics of Saint Peter Chrysologus are within the altar to the left. The more prominent central altar preserves a few bone fragments from the martyr Saint Cassian.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralSaintMarySydney', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralSaintPeterBologna', 'Cattedrale di San Pietro<br>Via Indipendenza 7, <br>40126 Bologna, Italy <br><br>The head of Saint Anne is said to rest within a reliquary in the second chapel on the right side of the nave.<br>In 1435 the King of England, Henry VI, gave this relic to the city of Bologna after their bishop, Blessed Nicolò Albergati, smoothed relations between England and France during the 100 Years’ War.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralSaintZeno', 'Cattedrale di San Zeno, Pistoia<br><br>In the Chapel of Saint James, in front of the Silver Altar, is a reliquiary, made by Lorenzo Ghiberti in Florence in 1407, and which holds a bone fragment considered to be an authentic relic of the apostle James the Great.<br>It had been given to Pistoia by Archbishop Diego Gelmírez of Compostella, considering the special ties he had with the bishop of Pistoia Atto, who had requested the holy patronage through Ranieri, a clergyman originally from Pistoia who was well inserted in the clergy of the cathedral in Compostella.<br>Two faithful lieges of bishop Atto, Mediovillano and Tebaldo, were given the task of carrying the jacobite relic to Pistoia.', 'Cattedrale di San Zeno, Pistoia<br><br>Nella Cappella di San Jacopo, davanti all’Altare d’Argento, vi è il reliquiario, eseguito a Firenze nel 1407 da Lorenzo Ghiberti, che custodisce la particola ossea ritenuta una reliquia autentica dell’apostolo Giacomo il Maggiore.<br>Era stata donata a Pistoia dall’arcivescovo Diego Gelmírez di Compostella, per la speciale considerazione che tale presule aveva per il vescovo di Pistoia Atto, il quale aveva avanzato la richiesta per ottenere il santo patrocinio tramite Ranieri, ecclesiastico di rilievo originario di Pistoia e ben inserito nell’ambiente del clero della cattedrale compostellana.<br>Incaricati di portare in patria la reliquia iacobea sarebbero stati due fedeli vassalli del vescovo Atto, Mediovillano e Tebaldo.', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralSalerno', 'Duomo di Salerno<br>Via Duomo 1 <br>84121 Salerno, Italy <br><br>The relics of Saint Matthew were brought to Salerno in 954 AD. The city continues to celebrate the anniversary of the transfer of his relics with an annual festival on May 6th. Throughout the year his relics can be visited in the richly decorated crypt of this church.<br> *Despite being the legitimate pope, Saint Gregory VII (d. 1085) was forced out of Rome in 1084 as a result of his ties to the Normans and the political pressures created by the Holy Roman Emperor, Henry IV, and the antipope, Clement III. A year later Saint Gregory VII died in this city as an exile. His remains now rest under an altar in the right transept of this church.<br><br>Despite being the legitimate pope, Saint Gregory VII (d. 1085) was forced out of Rome in 1084 as a result of his ties to the Normans and the political pressures created by the Holy Roman Emperor, Henry IV, and the antipope, Clement III. A year later Saint Gregory VII died in this city as an exile. His remains now rest under an altar in the right transept of this church. <br>*The relics of Saint Matthew were brought to Salerno in 954 AD. The city continues to celebrate the anniversary of the transfer of his relics with an annual festival on May 6th. Throughout the year his relics can be visited in the richly decorated crypt of this church.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralSyracuse', 'Duomo di Siracusa<br>Piazza Duomo 5, <br>96100 Syracuse, Sicily, Italy <br><br>In 1988 Syracuse received the left humerus bone of Saint Lucy (d. 304) from the Patriarch of Venice, Marco Cè. This relic rests within this church in a silver reliquary placed within the second altar on the right side of the nave. A separate reliquary exposed only on special feasts contains two additional fragments from the left arm of Saint Lucy. <br>Also said to be preserved at this church are the robe, the veil, and the little shoes of the saint.<br>Finally, each year on December 13th and also on the first Sunday in May a statue of Saint Lucy is carried with much festivity through the streets of Syracuse. Within the chest of this statue, which was created by Pietro Rizzo in 1599, are three fragments from her ribs.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralTermoli', 'Cattedrale di Termoli<br>Piazza Duomo 1, <br>86039 Termoli, Italy <br><br>*In 1945 the relics of Saint Timothy were rediscovered in this church beneath a marble tile that read, “Here rests Blessed Timothy disciple of the Apostle Paul.” It is believed that they were buried here in 1239 and then over the following centuries forgotten.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralTurin', 'Duomo di Torino<br>Via XX Settembre 87, <br>10122 Turin, Italy <br><br>*Blessed Pier Giorgio Frassati (d. 1925) is buried in the third chapel on the left side of the nave. <br>*Also kept in this church is the Holy Shroud of Turin. However, it is not often available for public veneration. The last opportunity occurred during the spring of 2015.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('CathedralVercelli', 'Cattredale di Vercelli<br>Piazza S. Eusebio, <br>13100 Vercelli, Italy <br><br>*This church is dedicated to Saint Eusebius of Vercelli (d. 371). During his life he strenuously opposed the heresy of Arianism. In 355 AD at a synod in Milan his refusal to accept Arianism led to his exile. During this time he suffered greatly especially at the hands of an Arian bishop in Syria. Some years later he was granted his freedom and eventually returned to Vercelli.<br>*An altar on the left side of the nave contains an urn with the remains of Saint Eusebius.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('CemeteryChapelMesero', 'Cappella del Cimitero di Mesero<br><br>Saint Gianna Beretta Molla (d. 1962) is buried next to her husband in a small chapel within the parish cemetery in Mesero, Italy.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('CenterSpiritualitySaintFrancesXavierCabrini', 'Centro di Spiritualità Santa Francesca Cabrini <br>Via Giosuè Carducci 50 <br>26845 Codogno, Italy <br><br>Nine years before arriving in America Saint Frances Xavier Cabrini (d. 1917) founded the Institute of Missionaries of the Sacred Heart of Jesus in this city. Today a small museum located at this center wonderfully preserves this event. Also located here is the relic of Saint Frances’ heart. It rests within the convent chapel just to the right of the main sanctuary. It is best to call ahead prior to visiting to reserve a tour.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChapelOurLadyGoodSuccessQuito', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChartreuseSerraSanBruno', 'Certosa di Serra San Bruno<br>Via Santo Stefano 1, <br>89822 Serra San Bruno, Italy <br><br>*Saint Bruno founded this monastery and spent the last ten years of his life here. In 1514 his relics were transferred to the main sanctuary of the church at this monastery where they remain to this day.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChiesaSanFrancescoTagliacozzo', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>The mortal remains of Blessed Thomas of Celano (d. 1265) are kept in a glass reliquiary for the veneration of the faithful.<br>Thomas of Celano was a Franciscan friar, poet and writer. He is known for having most likely composed the sequence <i>Dies irae</i>, and for having written two <i>Vitae</i> of Saint Francis of Assisi, a life of Saint Clare, and at least a couple accolades in honor of Saint Francis.<br><br>Upon passing, Blessed Thomas was buried in the church of the monastery of the Poor Clares of Saint John \"in Barri\", located on a mountain in the Varri valley which is currently situated between the towns of Pescorocchiano (RI) and Sante Marie (AQ). Here he lived the last years of his existence. The body was relocated at first to the nearby monastery \"Santa Maria del Piano\", and then in 1516 to the convent church of Saint Francis in Tagliacozzo, in the area of Marsica.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchBVMZeitoun', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchDomineQuoVadisRome', '<p class=\"justify\">The church is situated at the crossing of Via Appia and Via Ardeatina, in the place where, according to tradition, Jesus would have appeared to Saint Peter as he was fleeing from Rome to escape persecution by Emperor Nero. When the apostle asked  Lord, where are you going?” (“Domine, quo vadis?”), Jesus would have answered “I am going to Rome to be crucified again”. Saint Peter, having understood the reprimand, turned around and went back into Rome, where he was martyred. When Jesus disappeared, he left the traces of his footprints on a stone, a copy of which can be found within the church: thus the name “in palmis”. The original can be found in the nearby Basilica of Saint Sebastian outside the Walls. Founded in the 9th century, the church was rebuilt in the 16th and 17th centuries; it was at this time that the current façade was built.</p>', '<p class=\"justify\">La chiesa sorge all’incrocio tra la Via Appia e la Via Ardeatina, nel luogo in cui, secondo la tradizione, Gesù sarebbe apparso a Pietro in fuga da Roma per scampare alla persecuzione di Nerone. Alla domanda dell’apostolo “Signore, dove vai?” (“Domine, quo vadis?”), Gesù avrebbe risposto “Vado a Roma per farmi nuovamente crocifiggere”. Pietro, compreso il rimprovero, tornò indietro, affrontando il martirio. Gesù scomparve, lasciando però impresse le orme dei suoi piedi su una pietra, la cui copia è custodita all’interno della chiesa: di qui l’appellativo “in palmis”. L’originale si trova nella vicina Basilica di San Sebastiano fuori le Mura. Fondata nel secolo IX, la chiesa fu riedificata nel XVI e nel XVII secolo, quando fu realizzata la facciata nelle forme attuali.</p>', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchHolyApostlesRome', '<p class=\"justify>Chiesa dei Santi XII Apostoli<br>Piazza dei Santi Apostoli 51<br><br>Relics of Saint Philip apostle and Saint James the Less rest within the confessio of this church. During the 6th century they were transferred from Constantinople to Rome by Pope Pelagius I (d. 561). In 1873, as excavations commenced below the central altar, their relics were unearthed. They were then carefully examined and repositioned within the <i>confessio</i> where they rest today.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchHolyFamilySchio', 'Chiesa della Sacra Famiglia<br>Suore Canossiane<br>Via Fusinato 51, <br>36015 Schio, Italy <br><br>Saint Josephine Bakhita (d. 1947) began her life as a slave in Sudan. After gaining her freedom she became a nun in Italy and spent the last 45 years of her life in this Canossian convent. Her body now rests under the main altar of this church.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchHolyMaryInVallicellaRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Santa Maria in Vallicella (Chiesa Nuova)<br>Via del Governo Vecchio 134<br><br>In 1597 the skulls of Saints Nereus and Achilleus were given to this church. They rest within reliquaries in the sacristy and are sometimes brought out for public veneration on May 12th.<br><br>The additional remains of Saints Nereus and Achilleus had been stolen in 1870 from the church of Santi Nereo e Achilleo. These remains were recovered and are now said to rest within a porphyry urn under the main altar of Chiesa Nuova.<br><br>The body of Saint Philip Neri (d. 1595) is enshrined in the left transept of this church. His private rooms can be visited on certain days of the week. They are located in the right wall of the left transept.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchImmaculateConceptionRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa dell’Immacolata Concezione della Beata Vergine Maria<br>27 Via Veneto<br><br>Relics of Saint Justin the Martyr rest under the altar located behind the main altar. Kindly ask the sacristan for access. The remains of Saint Justin the Martyr were temporarily transferred in 1992 to the parish church of San Giustino a Centocelle in Rome. However, they have now been returned to this church.<br><br>The bones of nearly 4,000 Capuchin friars are located in the crypt.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchMaryMagdaleneRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa della Maddalena<br>Piazza della Maddalena, 53<br><br>In the third chapel on the right side of the nave are the remains of Saint Camillus de Lellis. He lived in the adjacent monastery and died here in 1614. His rooms can be visited by asking the sacristan. One of these rooms has been transformed into a chapel and contains the relic of his heart.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchMostHolyNameJesusRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa del Gesù<br>16 Via degli Astalli<br><br>An arm of Saint Francis Xavier (d. 1552) rests within a reliquary above the altar in the right transept. With this arm he baptized thousands of individuals in India and the Far East.<br><br>Saint Ignatius of Loyola (d. 1556), the founder of the Jesuits, is buried under the altar in the left transept. His rooms are located in the Generalate next to the church and may be visited.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchNameJesusNaples', 'Gesù Nuovo<br>Piazza del Gesù Nuovo <br>80134 Naples, Italy  <br><br>The remains of Saint Joseph Moscati (d. 1927) rest within a tomb placed within the second chapel on the right side of the nave of this church. In life he was a medical doctor and researcher who practiced great charity in his profession. In particular he was known to never charge the poor for his services. A museum just a short distance from his tomb preserves his memory. Within this museum are both the bedroom in which he died and his study. Also preserved here are many of the medical instruments that he used in life.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchOurLadyAiMontiRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Santa Maria ai Monti<br><br>Saint Benedict Joseph Labre, known as the \"wanderer of God\" (Amettes, March 26th 1748 – Rome, April 16th 1783), was born to a large family, in which the parents had a hard time making ends meet cultivating a portion of land and managing a small shop. An uncle priest gave him his first schooling.<br><br>Benedict Joseph requested to enter a trappist monastery but was not welcomed. He tried with a few other monasteries but was always sent back. He did a month in a Carthusian monastery but was again considered suitable. He succeeded in entering the Trappist Abbey of Sept-Fons as a novice, but eight months later he had to leave the monastery.<br><br>In 1770, while he was in Chieri, he understood that his vocation was to become a wanderer for God, preaching the Gospel by giving an example of humility and poverty. He so began to travel to the main shrines in Europe, going on pilgrimage to Germany, France, Spain and Italy: in shortly less than 14 years he seems to have traveled about 30,000 kilometers.<br><br>In Italy, he felt a close tie to the shrine of Loreto, but he also often visited Assisi, and to Bari to see the mortal remains of Saint Nicholas. In 1771 he went to Leuca, to pray at the famous shrine of Our Lady <i>de Finibus Terrae</i>.<br><br>He would sleep in the streets, living off offerings he would receive, even though he never begged for alms, and he would give to others anything he considered superfluous. He would dress in a simple manner, on his shoulders he would carry a satchel where he kept a few things to eat and the few things he possessed: a Gospel, a breviary, the Imitation of Christ, a few books of spiritual devotion and the rosary which he kept around his neck.<br><br>On December 3rd 1770 he arrived for the first time to Rome, where he stayed from 1777, taking up dwelling under an archway of the Colosseum. In a short time his spiritual fame spread throughout the city and his spiritual counsels were sought out by nobles and cardinals. An abbot, who had a hospice for vagabonds near the church of Saint Martin <i>ai Monti</i>, convinced him to stay there.<br><br>Romans considered him \"Our Lady\'s pilgrim\", or \"the poor man of the Fourty Hour devotion\", or \"the penitent of the Colosseum\". You could find him in the churches where the fourty hours devotion was taking place. According to the trinitarian fathers he also belonged to the Third Order of the Most Holy Trinity.<br><br>Considering the bad conditions in which he lived, his health declined and on Wednesday of Holy Week in 1783 he fell ill in the church of Our Lady <i>ai Monti</i>. He was taken to the back of a butcher shop in Via dei Serpenti by Francesco Zaccarelli, who called both for a doctor and for a priest. Around eight o\'clock in the evening Benedict Joseph passed away, at only 35 years of age.<br><br>A huge crowd attended his funeral, with people of every class.</p>', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Santa Maria ai Monti<br><br>San Benedetto Giuseppe Labre, detto il \"vagabondo di Dio\" (Amettes, 26 marzo 1748 – Roma, 16 aprile 1783), nacque in una famiglia numerosa, nella quale i genitori riuscivano a tirare avanti a fatica coltivando un pezzetto di terra e gestendo una piccola merceria. Uno zio parroco si incaricò di dargli i primi insegnamenti scolastici.<br><br>Fece domanda per entrare in un monastero trappista ma non fu accolto, provò con altri monasteri ma fu sempre respinto, fece un mese di prova in un monastero certosino ma fu giudicato non idoneo. Riuscì a entrare come novizio nell\'abbazia trappista di Sept-Fons, ma dopo otto mesi dovette lasciare il monastero.<br><br>Nel 1770, mentre si trovava a Chieri, capì che la sua reale vocazione era di essere come vagabondo di Dio, predicando il Vangelo con l\'esempio di un\'umiltà e povertà estreme. Cominciò così a viaggiare per visitare i più famosi santuari europei, e fece pellegrinaggi in Germania, Francia, Spagna e Italia: si calcola che in poco meno di 14 anni abbia percorso circa 30.000 chilometri.<br><br>In Italia, il santuario a cui era più legato era quello di Loreto, ma visitò spesso anche Assisi e Bari, per vedere le spoglie di San Nicola. Nel 1771 si recò a Leuca, per pregare presso il famoso santuario di Santa Maria de Finibus Terrae.<br><br>Dormiva per strada, vivendo di offerte anche se non chiedeva l\'elemosina, e donava ad altri tutto quello che considerava superfluo. Si vestiva in maniera semplice, sulle spalle portava un sacco in cui aveva qualcosa da mangiare e le uniche cose che possedeva erano: un Vangelo, un breviario, il libro Imitazione di Cristo, alcuni libri di devozione spirituale e il rosario che portava al collo.<br><br>Il 3 dicembre 1770 arrivò per la prima volta a Roma, dove si fermò stabilmente dal 1777, stabilendosi sotto un\'arcata del Colosseo. In breve tempo la sua fama spirituale si diffuse nella città e i suoi consigli spirituali furono richiesti da nobili e cardinali. Un abate, che gestiva un ospizio per vagabondi vicino alla chiesa di San Martino ai Monti, lo convinse tempo dopo a stabilirsi lì.<br><br>I romani lo conoscevano come \"il pellegrino della Madonna\", o \"il povero delle Quarantore\", o \"il penitente del Colosseo\". Lo si poteva incontrare nelle chiese dove si svolgevano le quarantore. Secondo i trinitari apparteneva anche al terzo Ordine della Santissima Trinità.<br><br>Viste le condizioni di stenti in cui era vissuto, la sua salute peggiorò e il giorno di mercoledì santo del 1783 si sentì male nella chiesa di Santa Maria ai Monti. Fu trasportato nel retrobottega di un macellaio di via dei Serpenti, Francesco Zaccarelli, il quale provvide a chiamare prima un medico, poi un prete. Verso le otto di quella sera il Labre morì, a soli 35 anni.<br><br>I suoi funerali videro la presenza di un\'enorme folla di ogni ceto. Tanta fu la gente che si recò a visitare le sue spoglie nella chiesa di Santa Maria ai Monti, dove fu esposto ', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchOurLadyInTrastevereRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Santa Maria in Trastevere<br>Via della Paglia 14<br><br>Relics of the two popes Saint Callistus I (d. 222) and Saint Cornelius (d. 253) rest under the main altar of this church. These relics are joined by others in particular those of the priest and martyr Saint Calepodius (d. 232).</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchOurLadyLadderRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Santa Maria della Scala<br>23 Piazza della Scala<br><br>The right foot of Saint Teresa of Avila (d. 1582) rests within this church in a beautiful chapel to the left of the main sanctuary. It was gifted to this church in 1617. (This chapel is not visible from the nave of the church and it is rarely open to the public. However, if one kindly asks the sacristan access may be granted. If the sacristan is not present he or she can be called at the neighboring convent door.)</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchOurLadyPeaceRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Santa Maria della Pace<br>Viale Bruno Buozzi, 75<br><br>The remains of Saint Josemaria Escriva (d. 1975) rest within this church. The church is not visible from the street. To enter ring at  Viale Bruno Buozzi, 75. A secretary will then direct you to the chapel.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchOurLadySinj', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchRedeemerFrancesCabriniRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa del Santissimo Redentore e Santa Francesca Cabrini<br>Via Sicilia 215<br><br>The skull of Saint Frances Xavier Cabrini (d. 1917) rests within this church. It is placed within a statue of her likeness that reposes within an urn on the right side of the nave.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintAmbroseDellaMassimaRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa Sant’Ambrogio della Massima<br>Via San Ambrogio 3<br><br>This church is located west of Piazza Venezia near the Fontana delle Tartarughe. It is set behind some buildings and is not easy to notice from the street.<br><br>The relics of Saint Polycarp (d. 155) are set in a marble memorial stone under the high altar.<br><br>Tradition also holds that this church rests on land that was formerly the location of a house owned by Saint Ambrose’s father and occupied by his older sister.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintBarnabas', 'Chiesa di San Barnaba<br>Via della Commenda 5, <br>20122 Milan, Italy <br><br>In this city Saint Anthony Zaccaria (d 1539) founded the Congregation of the Regular Clerks of Saint Paul commonly referred to as the Barnabites. <br>*Saint Anthony Zaccaria’s short life was marked by great compassion for the poor and an equally strong desire to share the Word of God. Just prior to his canonization in 1897 his remains were placed within the crypt of this church. Today some of these remains still rest within this church. They are placed within the statue of his likeness that rests below the main altar of this church. A majority of his relics, however, have been distributed to other Barnabite communities throughout the world.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintBartholomewTiberIslandRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di San Bartolomeo all\'Isola<br>Piazza San Bartolomeo<br><br>An arm of Saint Adalbert (d. 997) is currently enshrined in the chapel to the left of the main sanctuary. It rests within a little metal box placed under the altar of this chapel.<br><br>Relics of the apostle, Saint Bartholomew, rest within the red porphyry basin that supports the main altar.</p>', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di San Bartolomeo all\'Isola<br>Piazza San Bartolomeo<br><br>Un braccio di Sant\'Adalberto (d. 997) si trova nella cappella a sinistra del presbiterio. Riposa all\'interno di una piccola scatola di metallo che si trova sotto l\'altare di questa cappella.<br><br>Reliquie di San Bartolomeo apostolo sono custodite nel vaso di porfido sotto l\'altare principale.</p>', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintBlaiseRomualdFabriano', 'Chiesa di San Biagio e Romualdo<br>Piazza Daniele Manin 12, <br>60044 Fabriano, Italy <br><br>Saint Romuald (d. 1027) was originally buried near the monastic cell in which he died in Val di Castro. In 1466 his body was found still incorrupt; therefore, in 1481 his remains were brought to the nearby city of Fabriano. Today his relics rest within the crypt of this church.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintBridgetRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Santa Brigida a Campo de\'Fiori<br>96 Piazza Farnese<br><br>Following the death of her husband, Saint Bridget of Sweden (d. 1373) devoted herself completely to a life of prayer and service. After founding the Bridgettine Sisters in Sweden she felt compelled to visit Rome in order to seek official approval for her community. Her visit resulted in her permanently remaining in the city for the next twenty-four years until her passing in 1373. Today a few of her relics rest within this Bridgettine convent which still to this day is occupied by members of her community. Her body was returned to Sweden shortly after her death.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintCharlesAlCorsoRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa dei Santi Ambrogio e Carlo al Corso<br>437 Via del Corso<br><br>Saint Charles Borromeo, the great 16th century Archbishop of Milan, is honored in a special way within this church. A relic of his heart rests in a reliquary within an altar located behind the main sanctuary.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintClaudiusRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa San Claudio<br>Via del Pozzetto 160<br><br>A relic of Saint Peter Julian Eymard (d. 1868) is placed within a statue of his likeness that rests within an urn on the right side of the nave.<br><br>This church is managed by priests from the Congregation of the Blessed Sacrament which Saint Peter Julian Eymard founded in 1856.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintDominicMajorNaples', 'Chiesa di San Domenico Maggiore<br>Piazza San Domenico Maggiore 8, <br>80134 Naples, Italy <br><br>Saint Thomas lived in this priory from 1272-1274. Within the cell in which he lived is preserved the miraculous crucifix that exclaimed, “You have written well of me, Thomas.” Also within this same cell is preserved a bone from his left arm. Access to this cell is only given by special permission.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintEustorgiusMilan', 'Chiesa di Sant\'Eustorgio <br>Piazza di Sant Eustorgio, 1, <br>Milan, Italy <br><br>The remains of Saint Peter of Verona (d. 1252) rest within this church.', 'Basilica dei Santi Vincenzo e Caterina de\' Ricci<br><br>Agli inizi del Cinquecento sorse il monastero femminile domenicano dedicato a San Vincenzo Ferrer, che ebbe grande impulso alla metà del secolo per opera di Suor Caterina de\' Ricci.<br><br>La chiesa, ultimata alla fine del Cinquecento, venne completamente rinnovata dopo la canonizzazione di Caterina de\' Ricci (la cui spiritualità aveva tanto influenzato la società fiorentina e toscana, tanto da essere l\'esempio di misticismo più importante prima di Santa Maria Maddalena de\' Pazzi) nel XVIII secolo.<br><br>Con la sepoltura del corpo della santa sotto l\'altare centrale, la chiesa venne promossa a basilica minore.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintFrancesRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Santa Francesca Romana<br>Piazza di Santa Francesca Romana 4<br><br>The remains of Saint Frances of Rome (d. 1440) are in the crypt below the main sanctuary. Her skeleton is vested in the habit of the Oblate Sisters.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintGregoryArmenianNaples', 'Chiesa di San Gregorio Armeno, Napoli<br>There is a reliquiary with the skull of Saint Gregory the Illuminator.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintIgnatiusRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Sant\' Ignazio<br>8/a Via del Caravita<br><br>The remains of Saint Aloysius Gonzaga (d. 1591) rest under the altar in the right transept. His rooms are next to the church and can be visited by appointment.<br><br>The body of Saint Robert Bellarmine (d. 1621), a highly regarded Jesuit cardinal and theologian, rests under the altar in the third chapel on the right side of the nave.<br><br>The remains of Saint John Berchmans (d. 1621), the patron saint of altar servers, rest under the altar in the left transept.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintJeremiahVenice', 'San Geremia<br>Sestiere Cannaregio 290, <br>30131 Venice, Italy <br><br>In 1204 the body of Saint Lucy (d. 304) was brought to Venice. Currently her body is enshrined in the church of Saint Jeremiah on the side opposite the church entrance.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintJohnBaptistFlorentinesRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di San Giovanni Battista dei Fiorentini<br>2 Via Acciaioli<br><br>A relic of Saint Mary Magdalene’s foot rests in a shrine to the left of the main sanctuary. Also the left transept chapel is dedicated to Saint Mary Magdalene.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintJohnBaptistSaintBlaiseSacrofano', 'Chiesa di San Giovanni Battista e San Biagio <br>Piazza San Biagio, 10 / Via di Mezzo <br>00060 Sacrofano, Italy <br><br>*Some bones of Saint Justin the Martyr (d. 165) are said to rest within an urn under the main altar.<br>*Note: The parish San Giovanni Battista e Biagio has two churches in the center of Sacrofano. The larger church with a piazza claims to have some small relics of Saint Blaise. The smaller church, which is located in the historic part of the city and is simply called Chiesa di San Giovanni Battista, has the relics of Saint Justin the Martyr.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintLawrenceInDamasoRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di San Lorenzo in Damaso<br>Piazza della Cancelleria, 1<br><br>This church is believed to have been founded in the very home of Saint Damasus I (d. 384) whose remains now rest under the main altar.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintLinusVolterra', 'Chiesa di San Lino, Volterra<br>d. 76 AD<br><br>Successor of Saint Peter, second Pope', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintMartinRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di San Martino ai Monti<br>28 Viale Monte Oppio<br><br>The greater part of the remains of Saint Martin I (d. 655) were transferred from Crimea to this church in Rome. They now rest in the <i>confessio</i> below the main altar. This <i>confessio</i> also houses the relics of many other saints taken from the Catacombs of Priscilla.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintNicholasVenice', 'San Nicolo al Lido<br>Riviera San Nicolo <br>30126 Venice, Italy <br><br>Small bone fragments of Saint Nicholas (d. 350) rest within this church. They are placed within a beautiful funerary monument located in the main sanctuary. Three statues placed above this monument depict Saint Nicholas and two other saints whose relics are also preserved here.', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintPadrePio', 'Chiesa San Pio<br>Piazzale Santa Maria Delle Grazie <br>71013 San Giovanni Rotondo, Italy <br><br>The remains of Saint Padre Pio (d. 1968) rest in the crypt below Chiesa San Pio. This is the large modern church located at the far end of the piazza. The entrance to the crypt is on the right side of this church. <br>*On the other end of the piazza is Chiesa Santa Maria Delle Grazie. This is where Saint Padre Pio celebrated Holy Mass and heard confessions for 52 years of his life. Immediately to the right of this church is a newer church that was built in 1959. Below these churches is a crypt where the remains of Saint Padre Pio had previously rested. This location still attracts much veneration; however, his remains now rest below Chiesa San Pio as previously noted.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintPantaleonRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di San Pantaleo<br>Piazza San Pantaleo / Piazza dei Massimi 4<br><br>The relics of Saint Joseph Calasanz (d. 1648) rest under the main altar of this church. His rooms can be visited in the adjacent convent.<br><br>Saint Joseph Calasanz is uniquely known for setting up the first free public school in modern Europe. During his lifetime it was highly controversial to educate the poor. Some thought that it would only leave the poor more dissatisfied with their lowly tasks in society. Education was not seen as an opportunity for advancement. Saint Joseph Calasanz nevertheless persevered and was eventually appreciated and honored for his work.</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintPaulAllaRegolaRome', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintPaulMajor', 'San Paolo Maggiore<br>Piazza San Gaetano 76, <br>80138 Naples, Italy <br><br>The remains of Saint Cajetan (d. 1547) rest within a beautiful tomb in the crypt of this church. Access to this crypt is through a door to the right of the double staircase that leads into the church. Saint Cajetan was a religious reformer of the early 16th century. He and several others founded the Theatines in 1524.', 'Chiesa di San Francesco<br><br>I resti mortali del Beato Tommaso da Celano (d. 1265) sono custoditi in una teca di vetro, esposti alla venerazione dei fedeli.<br>Tommaso da Celano è stato un religioso, poeta e scrittore italiano. Frate francescano, è celebre per essere considerato il probabile autore della sequenza <i>Dies irae</i>, e per aver composto due Vitae di san Francesco d\'Assisi, una Vita di santa Chiara, e almeno due lodi del Poverello.<br><br>Alla sua morte, fu sepolto nella chiesa del monastero delle Clarisse di San Giovanni in Barri, situato su un monte della val de\' Varri, tra i contemporanei comuni di Pescorocchiano (RI) e Sante Marie (AQ), dove visse gli ultimi anni della sua esistenza. La salma fu dapprima traslata nel vicino monastero di Santa Maria del Piano e dal 1516 nella chiesa-convento di San Francesco a Tagliacozzo, nella Marsica.', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintPaulMartyrdomRome', '<p class=\"justify\">A church was first built here in the 5th or 6th century to memorialize the place where, according to tradition, Saint Paul was beheaded. According to a popular legend, his head bounced three times on the ground, and in those three spots, three fountains sprang forth; these still flow and are located in the church.</p>\r\n<p class=\"justify\">The church standing today was built at the start of the 17th century by the architect and sculptor Giacomo della Porta, as requested by cardinal Pietro Aldobrandini.</p>\r\n<p class=\"justify\">Inside the church the three fountains are yet extant, enclosed within three symbolic monumental covers in black marble, each at a different level. Near the first niche there is a pillar, which popular legend holds to be that to which Saint Paul was bound for his beheading.</p>', '<p class=\"justify\">La chiesa sorse nel sec. V-VI sul luogo dove, secondo la tradizione, San Paolo fu decapitato e la sua testa, rimbalzando tre volte sul terreno, fece scaturire ad ogni colpo altrettante sorgenti d’acqua: una calda, una tiepida e una fredda.</p><p class=\"justify\">L’edificio fu ricostruito all’inizio del Seicento da Giacomo della Porta, per volere del cardinale Pietro Aldobrandini.</p><p class=\"justify\">L’interno ospita ancora le tre fontane, racchiuse da altrettante edicole in marmo nero, poste su livelli diversi. Vicino alla prima nicchia, si trova la colonna dove, secondo la legenda popolare, San Paolo venne legato per essere decapitato.</p>', '', '', '', '');
