('ChurchSaintPeterInChainsRome', '<p class=\"justify\">The crypt, a small area under the main altar, seems to have been, according to some traditions, the place where Saint Peter was first imprisoned in Rome, before being transferred to the Tullianum (Mamertine Prison). Inside the crypt is the sarcophagus of the Seven Maccabee Brothers, jewish martyrs from the 2nd century B.C., venerated by christians and other eastern religions. The sarcophagus was most likely brought to Rome from Antioch by Pope Pelagius II. It was again found in 1876 during renovations to the chancel. The sarcophagus is divided into seven compartments each containing human remains, and bearing seals which indicated with certainty their authenticity. On the sarcophagus five scenes are depicted: The Resurrection of Lazarus, The multiplication of the loaves and the fish, The Samaritan Woman, Jesus announcing to Peter his betrayal, the <i>Traditio Legis</i>. Above the sarcophagus is a fresco by Silverio Capparoni (1876-77) which depicts the Martyrdom of the Maccabee brothers while their mother implores salvation for her last son. The crypt which is decorated with floral motifs is from the same period.</p>', '<p class=\"justify\">La cripta, piccolo spazio sotto l\'altare centrale, sembra secondo la tradizione, sia stato il primo carcere di san Pietro a Roma, prima di essere trasferito nel Carcere Mamertino. All\'interno della Cripta è custodito il sarcofago dei Sette Fratelli Maccabei, ebrei martirizzati nel secondo secolo a.c., venerati anche dai cristiani e da altre religioni orientali. Il sarcofago, probabilmente portato da Antiochia a Roma da Papa Pelagio II. Fu ritrovato nel 1876 durante i lavori di rifacimento del presbiterio, è diviso in sette scomparti contenenti dei resti umani e con dei sigilli che indicano con sicurezza la sua autenticità. Sul sarcofago sono scolpite cinque scene: La resurrezione di Lazzaro, La moltiplicazione dei pani e dei pesci, La Samaritana, L\'annuncio di Gesù a Pietro della rinnegazione, La consegna della legge. Sopra al sarcofago, un affresco di Silverio Capparoni del 1876-77 che rappresenta il Martirio dei fratelli Maccabei con loro madre che implora per la salvezza dell\'ultimo figlio. La cripta completamente affrescata con motivi floreali è dello stesso periodo.</p>', '', '', '', ''),
('ChurchSaintPraxedesRome', '<p class=\"justify\">Chiesa di Santa Prassede<br>Via di Santa Prassede, 9/a, 00184 Roma RM<br><br>The origins of the two basilicas with the titles of Saint Praxedes and Saint Pudentian are tightly related: the two roman saints were sisters, daughters of the Senator Pudens. The family relation becomes significant in reconstructing the origins of the two churches. The Basilica of Saint Pudentian, among the oldest in Rome, was built in the area of the ancient Vicus Patricius in the \"Monti\" district, near the current Via Urbana, almost at the start of the valley between the Viminal and Esquiline hills; it is therefore situated at the back of the grandiose Basilica of Saint Mary Major. It is possible that the Titulus Pudentis, instituted by Pope Damasus at the end of the fourth century, and for which there are undisputed historical documents, is derived from the alteration of the name of the original <i>domus ecclesiae</i> that was situated in the same place.<br><br>The Church of Saint Pudentian, among the first \"domestic churches\" instituted in the houses of the christian families of the origins, would therefore have been erected by Pope Pius I in 145 A.D., by the will of the two sisters who lived in the house which they in inherited from their father Pudens, who was a member of the powerful <i>Acilii Glabriones</i> family, in memory of the hospitality which the senator granted to Saint Peter and to Saint Paul around the year 70 AD. Saint Paul mentions Pudens at the end of the Second Lettere to Timothy. What is certain is archeological excavations and recent studies have confirmed the presence of two Roman <i>domus</i> underneath the foundations of the Basilica, one from the Republican era (2nd century B.C.) and one from the Imperial era (1st-2nd century A.D.), which would thus coincide with the tradition of the <i>Titulus Pudentis</i>. The young Saint Praxedes on the other hand, in the lateran <i>vicus</i>, not far from her sister\'s <i>domus</i>, also used a paternal inheritance to build a church for Eucharistic celebrations, the <i>Titulus Praxedis</i>, while the <i>Titulus Pudentis</i> would seem to have been built for the sole purpose of baptismal rituals.<br><br>Saint Praxedes used this church to hide christians who were persecuted by the then Emperor Antoninus Pius, providing for the burial of martyrs in the Cemetery of Priscilla, the catacombs of Saint Priscilla on Via Salaria. In this same Cemetery Saint Praxedes herself was buried along with her sister, to then be brought back to her church after being rebuilt by Pope Paschal I, who was elected Pope in the year 817 A.D. The existence of the <i>Titulus Praxedis</i> can be found in an epitaph dated 491 A.D., which confirms the importance in both the Republican and Imperial eras of the whole area around the current church of Saint Martin \"ai Monti\". Such importance was greatened by the building of the Basilica of Saint Mary Major under Pope Sixtus III (432-440 A.D.).</p>', '', '', '', '', ''),
